description.text:
This thing is a mounting plate for an optical Mega:Bit.

For details of what a Mega:Bit is, see http://www.pocketmoneytronics.co.uk/?page_id=398

The plate fits onto the front of a BBC micro:bit, and allows individual phototransistors to be positioned over each of the LEDs of the micro:bit LED matrix. These phototransistors can be used to control discrete LEDs, so that a larger scale micro:bit (Mega:Bit) can be controlled by the micro:bit.

The mounting plate is designed to work with these phototransistors - http://cpc.farnell.com/vishay/bpw85c/phototransistor-t1/dp/SC08561

For details of how to make a Mega:Bit, see the article on our blog site http://www.makerspace-uk.co.uk/megabit/

A massive thanks to David Whale (https://twitter.com/whaleygeek?lang=en) and Andrew Gale (https://twitter.com/PocketMoneyTron?lang=en) for their assistance in putting our version of their Mega:Bit together.

Aside from the IR Probe and the mount you will need a 2mm longer M3 screw to replace the stock screw. Please refer to the pictures to get an idea on how it is secured (component side should face away from the hot end).

As there there is just enough space to fit the sensor board below the carriage you will need to solder the 3 cables directly to the sensor board instead of using the supplied pin header. I recommend using 24AWG silicone cable for this purpose. Route these up between hotend and fans.
Adjust the distance between hotend and carriage if necessary to get the right clearance between probe and hotend.

Note: tested with the Raffle AluCarriage Dual but should work with the stock Makerbot carriage as well.

description.text:
This is part 3 of the Replicator 2/2X DuetWifi Upgrade series.
Part 1, 2 and 4 can be found here:

  • Part 1: DuetWifi Installation and PanelDue Mount (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2428995)
  • Part 2: Mini Differential IR Probe mount for Replicator 2X (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2475179)
  • Part 3: DuetWifi Configuration files for Replicator 2X (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2475257)
  • Part 4: Simplify3D Slicer Configuration for the Replicator 2X (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2476695)

This thing includes the config files I created for the Replicator 2X powered by the DuetWifi.
Before you use them please note the following:

  • My Rep2X is modified with a Raffle AluCarriage, Bottleworks HB and Flexion Extruder. As such you need to adjust the Bed Dimensions, Dual Extruder offsets, Home offsets and IR Probe offsets based on your final configuration. I have marked these in the files with to make them easy to find.
  • Autotune your heaters and use the new values
  • If you do not use the IR Probe, look in the files and follow the prompts to enable the legacy Z Axis Endstop

Files that need to be updated/modified for your machine (see above):

  • config.g
  • homeall.g
  • homez.g

Last but not least, post in the comments below in case you have questions. I will try my best to answer them frequently.

Have fun !

FAQ:

1: Have you replaced your end stops on X and Y i know about Z but Config seems to show them as NO not NC as they are.
A: No, the endstops are stock. As mentioned in the thing description there are 2 options for Z. Use the factory installed endstop (search the code for ) or IR probe homing for Z (which is the default setting in my config now). If you want to use the stock Z Endstop, you need to simply comment out the probe based Z homing and uncomment the switch based Z Endstop code in the config file provided.

2: Geometry on the Axis is compared to my stock firmware reversed. from LCD minus should move axes to left when looking at LCD your firmware does the opposite, not saying it is wrong but im just looking for answers.
A: Yes, I decided to put zero where the homing switches are. Rear right instead of the default rear left. Makes more sense in my opinion.

3: Speed on Z Axis could be improved but thats is just a minor detail.
A: Yes and no. It will reduce the sensor homing accuracy. If you go with the switch based homing you can increase it.

4: DC42 Z-Prope seems to not report back in Analog frequence? did you also connect to Z-Prope port
A: Yes, the DC42 probe is probe with an analog output connected to the Z probe connector. Probe mode is set to Mode 1 in the Firmware

5: Motor in reverse i think this is just because your connectors for nema turns otherway arround?
A: Yes, you need to update this based on your final wiring (I redid the complete wiring harnes in my machine to rule out issues due to the flimsy Makerbot wires. Most wires are now highly flexible silicone wires)

The cool thing is it zooms to an equivalent of 1200mm, which is just about perfect for photographing the moon, the Sun, or an eclipse like the one most of the USA will see on August 21, 2017. Don't want to use an SX530? No problem; the standard screw-thread mount version is now posted at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2485988 as a customizer script allowing you to specify the thread size of your lens.

title: Olympus 45mm f/1.8 lens hood (similar to LH-40B)

description.text:
This lens hood is a clone of the Olympus LH-40B, which is designed for the 45mm f/1.8 lens. It is reversible, and also clicks in place similar to the Olympus-hood. It is fairly tight, so may need to be tweaked depending on your printer's bias.

This is difficult to print, but is possible without supports. The lugs that connect to the lens are very overhanging, but I was able to successfully print it setting the lugs (2.5 to 4mm) to have a layer height of 0.05mm. I didn't get good results with a larger layer height.

The hood can be edited to place the lugs directly on the print bed, which would make it much easier to print.

The dimensions are based on photographs of the lens hood, and not the actual hood, so it could be tweaked somewhat. Also, the walls of the hood have been thickened until the hood is fairly stiff. They can be reduced (the thickness variable) if you'd like a more flexible hood.

As this is parametric CAD, it can be fairly easily adapted to other lens.

PS: If you own the official lens hood, I'd appreciate if someone could post measurements of the lens hood (as a comment) so that I can revise this model to be closer to the official hood.

A sculpture that, well, says something about influences. Read the instructions, there I'll explain what was going on in my head a little better.

So, many of you may know that we (the Makerbot tribe) spent some time "hacking" the Metropolitan Museum of Art, here in New York.
http://www.thingiverse.com/met It was really one of the most amazing experiences one could hope for. We were visited by many of the curators who shared their voluminous knowledge with us. We were all inspired, to say the least. While visiting the Southeast Asian gallery, we were shown one of the earliest examples of Buddhist sculpture. It had an distinctly Hellenistic influence,especially in the way the folds of cloth were rendered. This was a result of Alexander the Great, and the wide range of Greek exploration (as well as conquest, I digress).
As time went on, as we all know, Buddhist sculpture grew and evolved to become beautifully unique.
This led me to think about how now, in the 21st century , we are implementing wonderful technologies (in my case, a Makerbot)into the way we sculpt, and make art in general.
So, this piece is a combination of a Roman marble head*, scanned using 123D Catch, as well as a Lion from the Khmer Empire (Cambodia). I then added certain elements, including gears to express the influence of technology.
The end result is a unique piece that ties together periods of time separated by centuries into something that is both new and ancient.
If you're still reading this, I thank you, this is literally the longest description of a piece I made I have ever written.
Enjoy!
-Jason *http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:24752

description.text:
This is an enclosure for the Sparkfun Si-7021 I2C temperature / humidity sensor.

I was curious about the humidity levels inside a toolbox in my shop so I did what any respectable nerd would do: I set up a Raspberry Pi with a temp / humidity sensor. Now I can monitor and plot graphs of the temp and humidity in my toolbox from anywhere in the world. I also get SMS and EMail alerts if either goes out of range. And because this is inside the toolbox it doesn't have to look pretty - it only needs to protect the sensor from getting accidentally whacked by a tool.

This is a super simple design that only took a few minutes and it prints quickly with a larger layer height and not much infill. Remember that it just protects the sensor so it doesn't have to be pretty.

title: Ultimaker Alu bed with 3-point bed leveling (package)

description.text:
As I got a nice alu sheet I decided to build a new print bed out of it, incorporating a nice, nearly plug-in 3-point bed leveling.
Here I gathered all needed informtion/parts as a package:
  • Alu bed: dimensions and positions for M3 threads can be found in the pdf
  • Replacement parts for front bed mount as direct plug-in replacement
  • Rear bed mount parts (need to drill 3 holes in the plywood)
  • Bed washers from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:22448
  • M3 screw knob from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:225286
    Further you need:
  • 3 pc. Original bed springs
  • 3 pc. M3x40 mm screws or threaded rods
  • 6 pc. M3x10mm screws
  • 9 pc. M3 nuts
  • glass plate 242x242, thickness as you like, 2mm recommended
  • 2pc. bulldog clamp
  • 3mm drill for cleaning the guiding holes
    As I finished replacing my acrylic bed, I'm absolutely glad with this setup as it needs not too much space, less modification on the original parts and gives a very smooth and easy leveling.
    Next will be to add a silicon heater pad to get a heated bed

• Print all parts. You need:
    • 2x front mount
    • 2x front mount bottom plate
    • 1x rear mount
    • 1x rear mount bottom plate
    • 6x spring washer
    • 3x screw knob
  • Drill a 8mm hole exactly in the middle of the existing rear mount
  • Place rear mount into the hole and drill the coresponding 3mm holes for mounting it
  • Place rear bottom mount at the under side of the plywood and use 2x M3x10mm screws to mount the whole assambly. screw directly into the bottom plate, no nuts needed
  • Replace the two front mounts by the new parts, using each 2pc. M3x10mm and the bottom plate for mounting, no nuts required
  • Place 2 nuts in each screw knob and screw it onto the M3x40mm screws or rod, do this 3 times
  • Place the assambly from below through the new mountings, slide a spring washer, the spring, a second washer (take care about the orientation of the washers) onto the assabmly and secure it with an M3 nut each.
  • Screw down the nuts at least 6mm, place the alu bed onto the scews and screw them into the alu plate as deep as possible without getting out on the print surface.
  • Counter the position of the assambly/bed with the M3 nuts
  • Make sure, everything is working properly and there is no friction when pushing down the bed. If there is friction, take out the mounts and use the 3mm drill to make it work smooth...
  • TADAAAA.... ready for testing...

description.text:
After a friend designed a few 3d printed connectors for geodesic domes, I looked at and thought "That would be a fantastic parameteric." So I used this to teach myself scad and have been printing these since.

Select the type of geodesic dome you are building (1v or 2v), your strut material dimensions and shape, and this generates hubs and connectors. You can use an online geodesic dome calculator to come up with strut lengths.

This is NOT designed to be strong enough for climbing on or housing - you'd need steel or something like that. You might be able to cast a mold from these, however, particularly if you remove the "top" of the brace and cant the angles.

The connectors are labeled in the sockets for angles A and B.If I add 2V or 3V variants, the sockets will be labeled C & D as appropriate.

description.text:
Watch here: https://youtu.be/xbQJkHzL4nQ

The Cactus is finally joining the ranks of plants ready to defend my shelves against the incoming Zombie invasion. It's up there with the Sunflower and the Peashooter. Chomper will be joining soon!

I modeled it in ZBrush. I created the main body shape with ZSpheres and then I turned on Radial Symmetry on the Y axis to create the ridges around the body. Then I used the same technique to add the spikes and flowers all over. Then it was just adding the face details and we were done.

I printed it out on the Wanhao D7. I actually messed up the first time and didn’t hollow it out. Which would’ve been fine, but I waited too long to check it and it ended up using all the resin and stopped printing. That was an expensive mistake. But I hollowed out the model and kicked it off again. It turned out pretty good.

This is a perfect use for SLA because this model would’ve been extremely hard to sand properly with all the little spikes and flowers around it. So my wife barely had to sand at all before she could start painting. She started with primer, then moved to airbrush for the main colors, then finished up with paintbrushes for the details. If you want to know what equipment and paints she uses check the description for some links to what she uses.

• Print 1 pc. of bottom end with 5pc. of lids

  • Mount the bottom end to the rear plywood, in a way the platform can move without problems using screws or double sided tape
  • Mount the top end by using the lowest screw of the arm assambly

Components:
-Omnibus F4 micro. (Airbot)

-Runcam Owl (Runcam/Amazon/SecurityCamera200)
-T-Motor F20 (GetFPV)

-3.50inch / 88.90mm Propellers (Militia Brothers)
-1.2Ghz 200mW VTX (GetFPV)

-3M Commander (Amazon/Walmart)
-Millie-Ties (Amazon)
-27mm Standoffs (GetFPV)

I hope you all enjoy the build. Fly safely and responsibly, SHRED SOME ATMOSPHERE!

UPDATE: 09 August 2017_20:30 hrs
-The Omnibus F4 micro has a very noisy power supply. I added another low ESR capacitor paired with a 5 volt regulator, which in turn increased the up weight by <5 grams. Dry, the copter is almost close to weight with a Horizon Hobby Blade Torrent 110. I took her (Dark Sister II) out for a few flights with some Turnigy 3S 700mAh 60C (83 grams) and ReadyMadeRC 4S 450 mAh 60C (68 grams) batteries. The grip is amazing with 3S while slow flying, she was a jaw dropper with 4S. Overall, the copter feels like a light and overpowered full size mini-quad. If you have BetaFlight 3.1.7 installed on the flight controller and intend to drive with 4-cell batteries, you may want to go to configuration and drop the idle percent from the default of 4.50 to 1.00% as 4.50% made the copter bolter all over the place when armed.

Capable sub 250 gram screamer

Sometimes it's difficult to have all my copters flight ready, I figured it would be nice to have a small/compact quad that I can fly at work or whenever I make a pit-stop while travelling. The caveat of 3 inch quadcopters is that they are not suited for flight when winds travel at an excess of 5mph. Also, most 3 inch frames in the market are either too heavy with wide arms, or light but too fragile. I spent over 72 hours of work, trial and error, observations; REPR_Tepes went through many iterations. The final product was light, capable of spinning 3.50" propellers that improves grip and handling.

description.text:
The idea of this cabinet came from the fact that it is not that convenient for your family to have DIY laboratory at home. At the same time it was not convenient for me because all the staff was spread out across the house. The original idea is presented in STL file. I "ordered" a place at home from my family. This place is able to hold a cabinet at size 100cm x 80 cm x 240 cm (Width x Deepness x Height). The final cabinet was a slightly different from the original idea but it became even more powerful and convenient.
The base is a cabinet made from 18mm plywood. It has 3 levels. Level 1: it is bottom side. On the right hand is a box for CNC machine. The machine itself was described here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:80306. Machine is placed on a rolling platform and can came out of the box for the full size. I printed chain for wires (AC powers + USB) to keep all things at right place. On the left side I have 3 rolling boxes suitable for the storage. To keep using a maximum space all 3 boxes was designed without left & right sidewalls. Level 2: It is a main working area. It has rolling desk and place for all needed equipment (like soldering station etc.). It also incorporates 29in display and slim desktop PC. There is a big storage area just under the desk. I printed tool holders designed to be freely placed on the back side of the front doors of level 2. More about holders you can get here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:246988 Level 3: most important to have here two rolling boxes of similar size, left and right. On the right side the box is specially designed to hold Replicator2. Design allows to print inside the box, replicator is connected to UPS and to PC. There is also a small PLA storage area just near the printer. Rolling box on the left and regular place on the top are both for the storage. The cabined is plugged externally into AC power outlet. The AC and DC power was distributed inside the cabinet. LED lighting is used to light up everything. A special care need to be taken for the heat dissipation. I have big ventilation holes for this on the back (air IN)side and on the left side (air OUT). OUT is supported by 2x2 120mm funs.
It seams that Replicator box do not need an intensive ventilation. Printing inside the box eliminates all problems with sticking to the platform. I do not need helper disks any more. But it is suggested to have this tunning be in place http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:204997

title: E3D v4 & v5 & v6 liquid cooling mod

description.text:
I have been using E3D hot ends (dual) for a while. E3D hot ends are top notch, but they use fans, which sometimes cause warping or delamination especially when printing ABS. Converting to liquid cooling addresses the problem and also makes the hot end a bit shorter.
The 2.5 mm wide cut feature in the top part can be removed if your extruder design allows it. My release of the i3ext works fine with the cut feature removed.

The design is only for the top part of E3D hot end. Heat break, heat block and nozzle are original, buy them from e3d-online.com website.  
Then buy a water cooling sleeve from eBay for example. It is intended for R/C use, and for 20 mm motors.  
Assemble using the instructions from E3D website.
